tional governance across the region. Presenting studies from North Africa and the Gulf region, as well as comparative perspectives from Asia and Latin America, they show clearly that efforts to improve education—and thereby enhance economic development and broaden the base of citizenship on which more stable and effective systems of governance can be built—will fail until ruling elites are no longer able to increase their political and economic power at the expense of the greater good.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducation and statezArab countries. 0aEducationxEconomic aspectszArab countries. 0aEducationzArab countries. 0aEducational changezArab countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aAlaoui, Hicham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlaoui, Hicham, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBenstead, Lindsay J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Christopher M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiwan, Ishac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrindle, Merilee S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamaizia, Adel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Alisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohstall, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeber, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeijer, Roel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpringborg, Robert , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSpringborg, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitl